[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `X-Robots-Tag` response header controls how search engines and other automated crawlers index and display resources such as PDFs, images, and other non-HTML content.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It functions similarly to the `<meta name="robots">` tag, but is applied via the HTTP response header, allowing greater flexibility (e.g., for non-HTML files or server-wide rules).
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] You can also use other directives such as `noarchive`, `nosnippet`, or `noimageindex` depending on your needs.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Server configuration can apply this header selectively — for example, only on specific file types (like PDFs or images).
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The `X-DNS-Prefetch-Control` HTTP response header controls DNS prefetching, a feature by which browsers proactively perform domain name resolution on both links that the user may choose to follow as well as URLs for items referenced by the document, including images, CSS, JavaScript, and so forth.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The default behavior of browsers is to perform DNS caching which is good for most websites.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] If you do not control links on your website, you might want to set `off` as a value to disable DNS prefetch to avoid leaking information to those domains.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The HTTP `Public-Key-Pins` response header was used to associate a specific cryptographic public key with a web server to mitigate MITM attacks with forged certificates.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] It was removed from Chromium in 2018 and is unsupported by all modern browsers.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Remove any `Public-Key-Pins` or `Public-Key-Pins-Report-Only` headers from production.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Rely on Certificate Transparency (CT) and CAA DNS records, which provide superior compromise detection without the operational brittleness of pinning.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] When serving user-provided files, proper HTTP headers should be used to prevent unintended execution in the browser.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] These headers help reduce risks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and unintended file execution.
