[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] The Mozilla Observatory is an online tool which helps you to check your website's header status.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] SmartScanner has a dedicated test profile for testing security of HTTP headers.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] Online tools usually test the homepage of the given address.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] But SmartScanner scans the whole website.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/http-headers-cheat-sheet] So, you can make sure all of your web pages have the right HTTP Headers in place.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] A **web cache** (or **HTTP cache**) is a system for optimizing the World Wide Web.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] It is implemented both client-side and server-side.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] The caching of multimedia and other files can result in less overall delay when browsing the Web.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] A forward cache is a cache outside the web server's network, e.g. in the client's web browser, in an Internet service provider, or within a corporate network.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] A network-aware forward cache only caches heavily accessed items.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] A proxy server sitting between the client and web server can evaluate HTTP headers and choose whether to store web content.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] A reverse cache sits in front of one or more web servers, accelerating requests from the Internet and reducing peak server load.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] This is usually a content delivery network (CDN) that retains copies of web content at various points throughout a network.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) defines three basic mechanisms for controlling caches: freshness, validation, and invalidation.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] This is specified in the header of HTTP response messages from the server.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] Freshness allows a response to be used without re-checking it on the origin server, and can be controlled by both the server and the client.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] For example, the Expires response header gives a date when the document becomes stale, and the Cache-Control: max-age directive tells the cache how many seconds the response is fresh for.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] Validation can be used to check whether a cached response is still good after it becomes stale.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] For example, if the response has a Last-Modified header, a cache can make a *conditional request* using the If-Modified-Since header to see if it has changed.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] The ETag (entity tag) mechanism also allows for both strong and weak validation.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] Invalidation is usually a side effect of another request that passes through the cache.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] For example, if a URL associated with a cached response subsequently gets a POST, PUT or DELETE request, the cached response will be invalidated.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] Many CDNs and manufacturers of network equipment have replaced this standard HTTP cache control with dynamic caching.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] In 1998, the Digital Millennium Copyright Act added rules to the United States Code (17 U.S.C. §: 512) that exempts system operators from copyright liability for the purposes of caching.
[src:cache-poisoning-defense/web-cache] This is a list of server-side web caching software.
